<div class="indented"><a id="comment-4202540"></a>


<div class="non_toggle_area" id="comment-4202540">
  <div class="non_toggle_label">
       <span class="scomments_info">Sat, 11/30/2013 - 19:09 | <a href="/news/2013-11-30/russell-napier-we-are-eve-deflationary-shock#comment-4202540" class="active">4202540</a></span>
              <b><a href="/users/nuinut" title="View user profile.">nuinut</a></b>
  </div>

  <div class="comment-content">
    <div class="author"><div class="picture">
  <a href="/users/nuinut" title="View user profile."><img src="/sites/all/themes/newsflash/images/bagicon.png" alt="nuinut&#039;s picture" title="nuinut&#039;s picture"  /></a></div>
</div><div class="author"></div>
    <p>Russell Napier: <strong><em>"…one should expect one key major credit event to occur."</em></strong></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>Here's a feasible one that meets Russell's definition: the ECB defending the stability of the euro, their single and only mandate, and moving to prevent outright monetary deflation in the Eurozone with the last remaining tool at their disposal: printing euros to bid for open market gold.</p>
<p>The value of everything outside the HICP is beyond the ECB's mandate, but gold distinguishes itself by being <em>the very furthest item</em>&nbsp;due to its absence of utility, thus the one used in extremis. The ECB has a single priority: stability. When they run out of other tools, this is what they'll do.</p>
<p>CB gold reserves are&nbsp;<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chekov%27s_gun" rel="nofollow">Chekhov's Gun</a>.</p>
<p>Anton Chekhov: <strong><em>"<span>If it's not going to be fired, it shouldn't be hanging there.</span>"</em></strong></p>

  </div>
  <div class="links"><ul class="links"><li class="comment_forbidden first last"></li>
