<div class="non_toggle_area" id="comment-4204101">
  <div class="non_toggle_label">
       <span class="scomments_info">Sun, 12/01/2013 - 16:49 | <a href="/news/2013-11-30/russell-napier-we-are-eve-deflationary-shock#comment-4204101" class="active">4204101</a></span>
              <b><a href="/users/pareto" title="View user profile.">Pareto</a></b>
  </div>

  <div class="comment-content">
    <div class="author"><div class="picture">
  <a href="/users/pareto" title="View user profile."><img src="/sites/all/themes/newsflash/images/bagicon.png" alt="Pareto&#039;s picture" title="Pareto&#039;s picture"  /></a></div>
</div><div class="author"></div>
    <p>Price delfation was always a silver lining in a correction that comes as a result of the FED interfering in the market in the first place. &nbsp;To clear the monetary malfeasance prices have to fall because propping them up at $85B/month only delays the inevitable. &nbsp;When prices fall, collateral based on speculation falls to zero and real assets exchange hands (from the dumber to the smarter - or from the speculator to the producer). &nbsp;This is the mechanism by which markets fetter out crap and start anew. &nbsp;Inflating reduces the value of collateral since the level of collateral (real stuff) hasn't increased much as this site has demonstrated y/y. &nbsp;So as inflating rises, the collateral is spread thinner and thinner until there is no collateral left at all.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>There's no free lunch. &nbsp;That much I know and may be all I know. &nbsp;</p>

  </div>
